options.guidance: Create an HTML Summary of the top 5 most FalconGroupingTags and SensorGroupingTags for cs_neighbor_tags
options.script:
from collections import Counter from typing import List, Dict def main(input: List[Dict[str, any]]) -> str: """ Generates an HTML summary of the top 5 most frequent FalconGroupingTags and SensorGroupingTags from the provided cs_neighbor_tags data. Args: input (List[Dict[str, any]]): A list of dictionaries containing cs_neighbor_tags data. Returns: str: An HTML summary of the top 5 most frequent FalconGroupingTags and SensorGroupingTags. """ # Extract all FalconGroupingTags and SensorGroupingTags from the input data all_tags = [] for item in input: if item.get('cs_neighbor_tags'): all_tags.extend(tag for tag in item['cs_neighbor_tags'] if tag.startswith('FalconGroupingTags/') or tag.startswith('SensorGroupingTags/')) # Count the frequency of each tag tag_counts = Counter(all_tags) # Get the top 5 most frequent FalconGroupingTags and SensorGroupingTags top_falcon_tags = [tag for tag, count in tag_counts.most_common() if tag.startswith('FalconGroupingTags/')][:5] top_sensor_tags = [tag for tag, count in tag_counts.most_common() if tag.startswith('SensorGroupingTags/')][:5] # Generate the HTML summary html = "

Top 5 FalconGroupingTags

" html += "
    " for tag in top_falcon_tags: html += f"
  • {tag}: {tag_counts[tag]}
    • " html += "
" html += "

Top 5 SensorGroupingTags

" html += "
    " for tag in top_sensor_tags: html += f"
  • {tag}: {tag_counts[tag]}
    • " html += "
" return html

diagram_notes.content:
# Requirements
- CrowdStrike Read/Write API key scoped for Hosts
- A Tines Resource

# EDgaR Utility
A Security Analyst can:
-  check CrowdStrike to see if an endpoint is present by selecting Audit.
- tag endpoints in CrowdStrike by selecting Tagging.

An organization can use CrowdStrike tags to identify departmental asset owners which can be used in Incident Response, CrowdStrike Fusion Workflows or Scheduled Reports, such Spotlight Vulnerability Host reports.

# Asset Discovery -  Unmanaged  Neighbors 

- Schedule this workflow to generate a daily report.

The CrowdStrike Host API endpoint returns null if the FQDN of the host is not present in the console, if the FQDN of the hostname is queried.  It will return the host's FQDN if the hostname is used in the API call.  The Automatic mode ET strips the FQDN to ensure the host is returned in the results.
The Tines page uses the Conditions feature to hide tagging elements that may not be used or known by the analyst.

# Requirements

- Crowdstrike Read only API key scoped for Assets.
- A Tines Resource

# The CrowdStrike Asset Discovery API endpoint 
- discovers "unmanaged" neighbors, endpoints that do not have CrowdStrike installed on them.  

An endpoint with the Falcon sensor discovers neighbors whose IP is not present in the CrowdStrike Console.  

This API endpoint may be helpful in finding endpoints that do not have Falcon sensor installed to ensure EDR compliance.
# Change DATE Function to the correct time zone

This HTML summary assists the SecOps tean with identifying the top tags (Departments) that may have assets with no EDR.

fields.content:
EDgaR - the EDR Audit Utility.  
This workflow will check the CrowdStrike Console to see if the host is present.

fields.name: Hostname
fields.description: Enter a hostname.  If there are multiple hosts, use comma delimited notation with a comma after each host except for the last one.  If there are large number of hosts, please upload a csv.

fields.name: Heading
fields.content: EDgaR - the EDR Audit & Tagging Utility.

fields.name: Paragraph
fields.content: The workflow will check to see if the host is in CrowdStrike. If it is present, the workflow will tag the host with the appropriate Falcon Console tag. Please do not proceed with tagging if it is not clear what tag to use.  Please consult with the Data Governance team.

fields.name: File upload
fields.description: Upload a text or csv file with the header, hostname.  Each hostname needs to be on single line.

fields.name: Hostname
fields.description: Enter the hostname to tag.  If there are multiple hosts, use comma delimited notation with a comma after each host except for the last one.  If there are large number of hosts, please upload a csv.

fields.name: Departmental Code Tag
fields.description: This tag identifies the unit that owns the asset. This tag must be an Departmental code.

fields.name: Information Technology Asset Classification
fields.description: This tag identifies the IT classification of the asset from a business point of view regardless of the technical profile of the IT asset.

fields.name: Sub-Unit Tag
fields.description: This tag identifies the sub-unit to which this asset belongs. The usual tag follows this convention: "DEPT_SUB_XXX". For example, SecOps_SUB_WEB is an appropriate sub unit tag. Enter the sub-unit code for the sub-unit tag.

fields.name: Electronic Information Security Classification
fields.description: This tag identifies the security classification of electronic information (data) residing on or being processed by an IT asset.

fields.name: Electronic Service Risk Classification
fields.description: This tag identifies the risk classification of electronic services.

fields.name: Compliance External Tag
fields.description: This tag represents an asset where there are external statutory, regulatory, or contractual requirements to meet specific security standards.

fields.name: Paragraph
fields.content: Use the panel on the left to style and manage your page. Edit, sort, and delete page elements by selecting them on the page. And add new elements by dragging them from the left panel and onto the page.
